{
  "result": "At dawn, the city sounds like a machine clearing its throat. Buses hiss, shutters rattle, and someone somewhere tests a radio with a burst of old jazz. I like walking before the crowds arrive, when streets still belong to delivery drivers, bakers, and people who have reasons to be awake before sunlight is fully convinced. In those hours, everything seems possible, not because anything dramatic happens, but because nothing has hardened yet.\n\nA corner caf\u00e9 opens at six. The owner waters a stubborn basil plant, wipes the same spotless counter three times, and greets each customer as if they are returning from sea. I sit by the window and watch a cyclist balance a bouquet in one hand. A dog, immensely proud of a stick, parades past like a mayor.\n\nBy eight, urgency takes over. Faces tighten. Shoes click with purpose. Phones glow like tiny commandments. The spell breaks, but not completely. The morning leaves traces: steam on glass, flour on an apron, a trumpet phrase drifting from an upstairs apartment. These details are small, almost ignorable, yet they feel like evidence that life is more than deadlines and notifications.\n\nMaybe that is why I love early hours: they remind me that beneath every schedule there is a quieter rhythm, and if you listen carefully, the day begins as a poem before it becomes a list. Tomorrow I will wake again, lace my shoes, and borrow that fragile silence, hoping to carry one bright thread of it into noon traffic.",
